com.wm.xmldata

Class XmlDataElementTag

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataTag
      • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataContentTag
        • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataElementTag
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable

    public class XmlDataElementTag
extends XmlDataContentTag
    The XmlDataElementTag class constructs an XmlData element-tag from its constituent parts. There are methods that return the full-name as well as the path-name. The full-name is used in XmlData infosets. The path-name is used in map-paths and copy-paths; they contains additional qualifying information. The class may also be used to parse an element-tag into its constituent parts. In an XmlData infoset, element-tags are always paired with a simple-value, a group-value, or a complex-value, with the pair contained in a group-value.

    The element-tag full-name format is: 

         {particle-id}ncName#namespace
    where the particle-id identifies the position of this element-tag relative to all element-tags of the same name in a content model, ncName and namespace identify the element. For example, a content model might employ an element of the same name in the first and fourth position, with other elements in the second and third positions. 
     
     {1}able#smaple.org     signifies the first occurrence and
     {2}able#sample.org     signifies the fourth occurrence.
    The element-tag path-name format is 
     
     {particle-id}ncName#namespace[index]
    It includes an additional property: index specifies an offset into an array of repeating values. In a copy-path, the index may also be an index-iterator. For example: 
     
     {1}city[3]         references the 1st city tag, 4th repeating value
     {1}location[!x]    in a copy-map uses the index-iterator !x to iteratively access the members of the repeating value

    • Method Detail

      • createFromPath

        public static XmlDataElementTag createFromPath(java.lang.String name)
        Create an XmlDataElementTag from its String representation. Its form is {particleId}ncName#namespace[index] where:
        • particleId is the particle-id starting at 1
        • ncName is the XML local name
        • namespace is the XML namespace
        • index -- the tag value index (starting at 0 or a symbolic iterator-tag
        This constructor may not be used if the namespace contains the index bracket characters '[' or ']', or the path separator '/' unless they are expressed as % escapes. Use %2F for /, %5B for [, %5D for ], and %25 for %. Otherwise, the explicit constructor must be used, for example XmlDataElementTag(String, String, int) The # is omitted when there is no namespace. If particleId is omitted, it defaults to {1}. There is no default for index. When omitted, such tags are unindexed. Examples: 
        {3}employee
brother#family[2]
assets[!x]
        Parameters:
        name - the literal name
        Returns:
        an XmlDataElementTag
        See Also:
        createFromPath(String, XmlNamespaceMap), createFromPath(String, String)

      • createFromPath

        Create a XmlData element-tag using prefix notation. The method operates identically to createFromPath(String, XmlNamespaceMap) but the namespace map is specified as a String containing prefix/namespace pairs.
        Parameters:

        the constructed XmlDataElementTag

      • createFromPath

        public static XmlDataElementTag createFromPath(java.lang.String name,
                                               XmlNamespaceMap nsDecls)
        Create an XmlDataElementTag from its String representation using prefix notation and an XmlNamespaceMap. Its form is {particleId}prefix:ncName[index] where:
        • particleId is the particle-id starting at 1
        • prefix the prefix as defined by the XmlNamespaceMap
        • ncName the local name
        • index the repeating value value index (starting at 0 or an index-iterator
        The : is omitted when there is no namespace. If particleId is omitted, it defaults to {1}. The index and qualifier never appear in the instance tag; they are used only in the tag to provide addition information to methods. This form of the constructor may be used with any namespace characters. The namespace is assigned to a prefix by the nsDecla argument. If particleId is omitted, it defaults to {1}. There is no default for index or qualifier; when not specified, such tags are unindexed and unqualified. Examples: 
        {3}employee
ns:brother[2]
assets[!x]
        Parameters:
        name - the literal name
        nsDecls - an XmlNamespaceMap
        Returns:
        an XmlDataElementTag
